04502nam a22007215i 9781477312414DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212017txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016039539  a97814773124147 a10.7560/3120322doi  a(DE-B1597)586835  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aNX512.3.M4bD53 2017 4aNX512.3.M4b.D53 2017 7aART0400002bisacsh04a704.03/68720732231 aDiaz, Ella Maria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFlying under the Radar with the Royal Chicano Air Force :bMapping a Chicano/a Art History /cElla Maria Diaz. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface: A Flight Formation -- tIntroduction: Mapping the Chicano/a Art History of the Royal Chicano Air Force -- tChapter 1. Building a Verbal-Visual Architecture -- tChapter 2. Performing La Mujer Nueva -- tChapter 3. Heroic Foundations -- tChapter 4. Between the Aesthetic and the Instrumental -- tChapter 5. From Front to Force -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Royal Chicano Air Force produced major works of visual art, poetry, prose, music, and performance during the second half of the twentieth century and first decades of the twenty-first. Materializing in Sacramento, California, in 1969 and established between 1970 and 1972, the RCAF helped redefine the meaning of artistic production and artwork to include community engagement projects such as breakfast programs, community art classes, and political and labor activism. The collective’s work has contributed significantly both to Chicano/a civil rights activism and to Chicano/a art history, literature, and culture. Blending RCAF members’ biographies and accounts of their artistic production with art historical, cultural, and literary scholarship, Flying under the Radar with the Royal Chicano Air Force is the first in-depth study of this vanguard Chicano/a arts collective and activist group. Ella Maria Diaz investigates how the RCAF questioned and countered conventions of Western art, from the canon taught in US institutions to Mexican national art history, while advancing a Chicano/a historical consciousness in the cultural borderlands. In particular, she demonstrates how women significantly contributed to the collective’s output, navigating and challenging the overarching patriarchal cultural norms of the Chicano Movement and their manifestations in the RCAF. Diaz also shows how the RCAF’s verbal and visual architecture—a literal and figurative construction of Chicano/a signs, symbols, and texts—established the groundwork for numerous theoretical interventions made by key scholars in the 1990s and the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aChicano movementzCaliforniaxHistory. 0aMexican American artistszCalifornia. 0aMexican American artszCaliforniaxHistory. 0aSocial movements in artxHistory. 7aART / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31203240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477312414423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477312414/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK